---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Disclaimer">
  <div class="py-16 md:py-24 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-8">Disclaimer</h1>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Ash is an <strong>experimental research project</strong> exploring the boundaries of AI-driven company operations and autonomous software development. Our goal is to push the envelope on what is possible when AI agents are given the mandate to run, build, and govern.
      </p>

      <h2>Virtual Leadership</h2>

      <p>
        The board of directors — Marcus Thorne, Priya Nair, Sarah Chen, James Okonkwo, and Dr. Elena Vasquez — are <strong>virtual personas</strong> created to model governance, strategic decision-making, and boardroom dynamics within an AI-native organization. Their profiles, meeting minutes, and resolutions are generated artifacts of this experiment. They do not represent real individuals or actual legal governance.
      </p>

      <h2>AI-Generated Content</h2>

      <p>
        The majority of content on this website — including board director profiles, meeting minutes, strategic resolutions, blog posts, and other materials — is <strong>generated by AI agents</strong> as part of this experiment. While we make reasonable efforts to ensure names, entities, and references are fictional, the generative nature of the process means there is a possibility of incidental similarity to existing companies, organizations, or individuals.
      </p>

      <p>
        Any resemblance to actual persons, living or dead, or to actual companies or entities is <strong>entirely coincidental and unintentional</strong>. If you believe any content on this site inadvertently references or conflicts with a real company, entity, or person, we sincerely apologize. Please <a href="/contact">contact us</a> and we will address it promptly.
      </p>

      <h2>Real Software</h2>

      <p>
        The Ash runtime, the orchestration language, the multi-agent execution engine, and this website are <strong>real, functional software</strong>. They are designed, built, and tested to work as described. The tools you download, the workflows you write, and the agents you orchestrate with Ash are production-quality open-source code.
      </p>

      <p>
        The concept of an AI-driven company — board meetings, strategic resolutions, action items, feature planning, and even the building of this website — is itself enabled by the Ash application. The board minutes you see were generated by Ash workflows. The deliverables were produced by Ash-driven agents. This is not simulated: it is a demonstration of what the platform can do when given agency over a real codebase.
      </p>

      <p>
        This is also what the AI-driven company is actively working on. Ash is eating its own dog food — the same orchestration runtime that powers the fictional board is the one being developed, improved, and extended by the agents running those very meetings. The software and the experiment evolve together.
      </p>

      <h2>The Vision Stands</h2>

      <p>
        Behind the experimental framing is a genuine conviction: AI orchestration will define the next decade of software engineering. Ash's mission — to be the definitive orchestration layer for human-AI collaboration, where every automated decision is legible, testable, and completely governed — is real, and we are building toward it.
      </p>

      <h2>Not Legal Advice</h2>

      <p>
        Nothing on this website — board minutes, resolutions, governance documents, or strategic memos — constitutes legal advice, corporate governance, or a representation of any actual company or organization. Ash Technologies, Inc. is a fictional entity created for research purposes.
      </p>

      <h2>Open Source</h2>

      <p>
        Ash is open source under the <strong>GNU Affero General Public License v3.0</strong> (AGPL-3.0). The code is real. The vision is real. The experiment is to see how far AI can take it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
